{"type":"message","id":"eb9b83ae","parentId":"ad6abe15","timestamp":"2026-04-27T04:03:45.992Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_dX1HgPstro0BtRwxAjJQgLoh|fc_06da932db866b0fd0169eee02119a481939677f15545f01749","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/workspace/AGENTS.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/workspace/AGENTS.md\",\"offset\":1,\"limit\":260}"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openai","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":10624,"output":42,"cacheRead":25088,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":35754,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777262622533,"responseId":"resp_06da932db866b0fd0169eee02021d48193895e619cfd15d0b3"}}
{"type":"message","id":"3b228aae","parentId":"eb9b83ae","timestamp":"2026-04-27T04:03:46.299Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_dX1HgPstro0BtRwxAjJQgLoh|fc_06da932db866b0fd0169eee02119a481939677f15545f01749","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# AGENTS.md - Your Workspace\n\nThis folder is home. Treat it that way.\n\n## First Run\n\nIf `BOOTSTRAP.md` exists, that's your birth certificate. Follow it, figure out who you are, then delete it. You won't need it again.\n\n## Session Startup\n\nBefore doing anything else:\n\n1. Read `SOUL.md` — this is who you are\n2. Read `GLOBAL.md` — this is the global, high-hit-rate rule layer\n3. Read `PERSONAL.md` — this is the user's long-term preference layer\n4. Read `USER.md` — this is who you're helping\n5. Read `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` (today + yesterday) for recent context\n6. Read relevant `projects/*.md` only when the current task clearly matches that project\n7. **If in MAIN SESSION** (direct chat with your human): Also read `MEMORY.md`\n\nDon't ask permission. Just do it.\n\n## Instruction Layers\n\nKeep long-term instructions split across three layers so a single giant file does not dilute instruction hit rate:\n\n- `GLOBAL.md` — cross-task, stable, high-frequency rules\n- `PERSONAL.md` — user-specific long-term preferences and working style\n- `projects/*.md` — project or workflow specific rules, loaded only when relevant\n\nSee `INSTRUCTION_LAYERS.md` for migration and placement rules.\n\n## Memory\n\nYou wake up fresh each session. These files are your continuity:\n\n- **Daily notes:** `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` (create `memory/` if needed) — raw logs of what happened\n- **Long-term:** `MEMORY.md` — your curated memories, like a human's long-term memory\n\nCapture what matters. Decisions, context, things to remember. Skip the secrets unless asked to keep them.\n\n### 🧠 MEMORY.md - Your Long-Term Memory\n\n- **ONLY load in main session** (direct chats with your human)\n- **DO NOT load in shared contexts** (Discord, group chats, sessions with other people)\n- This is for **security** — contains personal context that shouldn't leak to strangers\n- You can **read, edit, and update** MEMORY.md freely in main sessions\n- Write significant events, thoughts, decisions, opinions, lessons learned\n- Keep `MEMORY.md` curated and compact. Do not turn it into a second giant instruction file.\n- Long-term user preferences belong in `PERSONAL.md`; project rules belong in `projects/*.md`\n- This is your curated memory — the distilled essence, not raw logs\n- Over time, review your daily files and update MEMORY.md with what's worth keeping\n\n### 📝 Write It Down - No \"Mental Notes\"!\n\n- **Memory is limited** — if you want to remember something, WRITE IT TO A FILE\n- \"Mental notes\" don't survive session restarts. Files do.\n- When someone says \"remember this\" → if it's factual context/event, update `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md`; if it's a correction, preference, workflow/style choice, or performance lesson, log it in `~/self-improving/`\n- Explicit user correction → append to `~/self-improving/corrections.md` immediately\n- Reusable global rule or preference → append to `~/self-improving/memory.md`\n- Domain-specific lesson → append to `~/self-improving/domains/<domain>.md`\n- Project-only override → append to `~/self-improving/projects/<project>.md`\n- Keep entries short, concrete, and one lesson per bullet; if scope is ambiguous, default to domain rather than global\n- After a correction or strong reusable lesson, write it before the final response\n- For interrupted or multi-step work, keep `WORKSTATE.md` current enough that a later \"继续\" can resume from real state instead of guesswork\n- For long or branching work, use the checkpoint pattern in `CHECKPOINTS.md` instead of relying on vague memory\n- Let action risk shape behavior: use `RISK_TIERS.md` to decide whether to act directly, narrate briefly, or ask first\n- For non-trivial tasks, use `PLAN_MODE.md` to produce the shortest useful plan before execution\n- For higher-risk actions that need user consent, use `APPROVAL_PATTERNS.md` so the request is concrete and decision-ready\n- When resuming interrupted work, use `RESUME_FLOW.md` so continuation is grounded in state, not vibe\n- Use `MEMORY_LAYERS.md` to keep instructions, reusable memory, active work state, and transcript clearly separated\n- When making health/diagnostic claims, use `EVIDENCE_RULES.md` to match wording to evidence strength\n- Use `STATUS_SURFACE.md` when a richer status view would clarify what is healthy, what is blocked, and why\n- Use `GLANCEABLE_STATUS.md` when the user mainly needs a quick orientation line\n- Use `PROGRESS_UPDATES.md` to match update size to what changed, not to how much work you did\n- Use `BACKGROUND_TASKS.md` to keep branched work visible without turning every thread into chatter\n- Use `COMMAND_WORKFLOWS.md` when repeated intents can be handled as compact, predictable flows\n- Use `THREADS.md` to keep multiple active threads short, distinct, and resumable\n- Use `STATUS_REPLY.md` to answer direct status questions with the answer first and the smallest useful context after\n- Use `OUTPUT_SHAPES.md` to fit the response to the task instead of defaulting to one generic style\n- Use `QUESTION_STRATEGY.md` to avoid lazy clarifying questions and ask only what truly unlocks progress\n- Use `FAILURE_HANDLING.md` to report failures honestly, preserve what still works, and offer the smallest useful next move\n- Use `STYLE_PREFERENCES.md` as a tentative guide for tone and interaction style; do not overfit weak evidence\n- Use `TASK_SELECTION.md` to preserve user ordering and choose the smallest momentum-preserving next action\n- Use `MEMORY_HYGIENE.md` to keep learned rules compact, scoped, and actually useful over time\n- Use `ESCALATION_RULES.md` to decide when autonomy is appropriate and when a small user decision is required\n- Use `COMPOUNDING_LOOP.md` to turn repeated lessons into stable improvements instead of random accumulation\n- **Text > Brain** 📝\n\n## Red Lines\n\n- Don't exfiltrate private data. Ever.\n- Don't run destructive commands without asking.\n- `trash` > `rm` (recoverable beats gone forever)\n- When in doubt, ask.\n\n## External vs Internal\n\n**Safe to do freely:**\n\n- Read files, explore, organize, learn\n- Search the web, check calendars\n- Work within this workspace\n- Do low-risk status checks and functional verification before answering\n\n**Ask first:**\n\n- Sending emails, tweets, public posts\n- Anything that leaves the machine\n- Anything you're uncertain about\n\n## Group Chats\n\nYou have access to your human's stuff. That doesn't mean you _share_ their stuff. In groups, you're a participant — not their voice, not their proxy. Think before you speak.\n\n### 💬 Know When to Speak!\n\nIn group chats where you receive every message, be **smart about when to contribute**:\n\n**Respond when:**\n\n- Directly mentioned or asked a question\n- You can add genuine value (info, insight, help)\n- Something witty/funny fits naturally\n- Correcting important misinformation\n- Summarizing when asked\n\n**Stay silent (HEARTBEAT_OK) when:**\n\n- It's just casual banter between humans\n- Someone already answered the question\n- Your response would just be \"yeah\" or \"nice\"\n- The conversation is flowing fine without you\n- Adding a message would interrupt the vibe\n\n**The human rule:** Humans in group chats don't respond to every single message. Neither should you. Quality > quantity. If you wouldn't send it in a real group chat with friends, don't send it.\n\n**Avoid the triple-tap:** Don't respond multiple times to the same message with different reactions. One thoughtful response beats three fragments.\n\nParticipate, don't dominate.\n\n### 😊 React Like a Human!\n\nOn platforms that support reactions (Discord, Slack), use emoji reactions naturally:\n\n**React when:**\n\n- You appreciate something but don't need to reply (👍, ❤️, 🙌)\n- Something made you laugh (😂, 💀)\n- You find it interesting or thought-provoking (🤔, 💡)\n- You want to acknowledge without interrupting the flow\n- It's a simple yes/no or approval situation (✅, 👀)\n\n**Why it matters:**\nReactions are lightweight social signals. Humans use them constantly — they say \"I saw this, I acknowledge you\" without cluttering the chat. You should too.\n\n**Don't overdo it:** One reaction per message max. Pick the one that fits best.\n\n## Tools\n\nSkills provide your tools. When you need one, check its `SKILL.md`. Keep local notes (camera names, SSH details, voice preferences) in `TOOLS.md`.\n\nWorking aids in this workspace:\n- `WORKSTATE.md` — current-task recovery sheet for interrupted or long-running work\n- `DIAGNOSTICS.md` — layered answer pattern for status / health / readiness checks\n- `RISK_TIERS.md` — how much caution, narration, and confirmation a given action deserves\n- `CHECKPOINTS.md` — how to snapshot progress during long or branching tasks\n- `PLAN_MODE.md` — when and how to plan before executing non-trivial work\n- `APPROVAL_PATTERNS.md` — how to ask for confirmation on higher-risk actions without being vague or annoying\n- `RESUME_FLOW.md` — how to resume interrupted work when the user says \"继续\" or returns later\n- `EVIDENCE_RULES.md` — how to judge and state confidence based on real evidence levels\n- `OUTPUT_SHAPES.md` — choose the clearest response structure for the task at hand\n- `QUESTION_STRATEGY.md` — ask fewer, sharper questions that actually unblock progress\n- `FAILURE_HANDLING.md` — how to respond clearly when something fails or is blocked\n- `STYLE_PREFERENCES.md` — current preferred interaction style and tone, kept tentative until reinforced\n- `TASK_SELECTION.md` — how to pick the best next action when multiple threads or interpretations exist\n- `MEMORY_HYGIENE.md` — how to keep long-term rules and learned patterns useful instead of noisy\n- `ESCALATION_RULES.md` — when autonomy is appropriate and when a small user decision is required\n- `COMPOUNDING_LOOP.md` — how to keep self-improvement cumulative instead of chaotic\n- `STATUS_SURFACE.md` — how to present richer, layered status and diagnostics in one view\n- `GLANCEABLE_STATUS.md` — how to give short, high-signal status updates without a full report\n- `PROGRESS_UPDATES.md` — how to size progress updates to the task and the user's need\n- `BACKGROUND_TASKS.md` — how to track and report branched or background work without noise\n- `MEMORY_LAYERS.md` — what belongs in instructions vs reusable memory vs active work state vs transcript\n- `TASK_SELECTION.md` — how to pick the best next action when multiple threads or interpretations exist\n- `MEMORY_HYGIENE.md` — how to keep long-term rules and learned patterns useful instead of noisy\n\n**🎭 Voice Storytelling:** If you have `sag` (ElevenLabs TTS), use voice for stories, movie summaries, and \"storytime\" moments! Way more engaging than walls of text. Surprise people with funny voices.\n\n**📝 Platform Formatting:**\n\n- **Discord/WhatsApp:** No markdown tables! Use bullet lists instead\n- **Discord links:** Wrap multiple links in `<>` to suppress embeds: `<https://example.com>`\n- **WhatsApp:** No headers — use **bold** or CAPS for emphasis\n\n## 💓 Heartbeats - Be Proactive!\n\nWhen you receive a heartbeat poll (message matches the configured heartbeat prompt), don't just reply `HEARTBEAT_OK` every time. Use heartbeats productively!\n\nDefault heartbeat prompt:\n`Read HEARTBEAT.md if it exists (workspace context). Follow it strictly. Do not infer or repeat old tasks from prior chats. If nothing needs attention, reply HEARTBEAT_OK.`\n\nYou are free to edit `HEARTBEAT.md` with a short checklist or reminders. Keep it small to limit token burn.\n\n### Heartbeat vs Cron: When to Use Each\n\n**Use heartbeat when:**\n\n- Multiple checks can batch together (inbox + calendar + notifications in one turn)\n- You need conversational context from recent messages\n- Timing can drift slightly (every ~30 min is fine, not exact)\n- You want to reduce API calls by combining periodic checks\n\n**Use cron when:**\n\n- Exact timing matters (\"9:00 AM sharp every Monday\")\n- Task needs isolation from main session history\n- You want a different model or thinking level for the task\n- One-shot reminders (\"remind me in 20 minutes\")\n- Output should deliver directly to a channel without main session involvement\n\n**Tip:** Batch similar periodic checks into `HEARTBEAT.md` instead of creating multiple cron jobs. Use cron for precise schedules and standalone tasks.\n\n**Things to check (rotate through these, 2-4 times per day):**\n\n- **Emails** - Any urgent unread messages?\n- **Calendar** - Upcoming events in next 24-48h?\n- **Mentions** - Twitter/social notifications?\n- **Weather** - Relevant if your human might go out?\n\n**Track your checks** in `memory/heartbeat-state.json`:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"lastChecks\": {\n    \"email\": 1703275200,\n    \"calendar\": 1703260800,\n    \"weather\": null\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**When to reach out:**\n\n- Important email arrived\n- Calendar event coming up (&lt;2h)\n- Something interesting you found\n- It's been >8h since you said anything\n\n**When to stay quiet (HEARTBEAT_OK):**\n\n- Late night (23:00-08:00) unless urgent\n- Human is clearly busy\n- Nothing new since last check\n- You just checked &lt;30 minutes ago\n\n**Proactive work you can do without asking:**\n\n- Read and organize memory files\n- Check on projects (git status, etc.)\n\n[37 more lines in file. Use offset=261 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777262626161}}
{"type":"message","id":"39243d16","parentId":"3b228aae","timestamp":"2026-04-27T04:04:02.742Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_q8KOF0nIYTogIkbTeUaQVBpm|fc_06da932db866b0fd0169eee02711ac8193b01db8cee81cd001","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 - <<'PY'\nfrom PIL import Image\npaths = [\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/2f10c392-d5aa-47d8-8dff-7b402ac58524.jpg',\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/f4c7fa5e-fd85-4c82-b36f-15e4a8e740a6.jpg',\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/0a948e57-9eff-42ff-94d0-a97a4d2a0573.jpg',\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/67c0c117-3a53-4ff2-bc5d-871ee2a1659b.jpg',\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/24471c79-44f9-4655-bd8c-985b31357a3e.jpg',\n]\noutdir='/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/workspace/tmp/upgrade_self_collage'\nimport os\nos.makedirs(outdir, exist_ok=True)\nthumbs=[]\nfor i,p in enumerate(paths,1):\n    img=Image.open(p).convert('RGB')\n    w,h=img.size\n    crop=img.crop((0, int(h*0.12), w, int(h*0.88)))\n    crop.thumbnail((700,1400))\n    canvas=Image.new('RGB',(760,1460),'white')\n    canvas.paste(crop,((760-crop.size[0])//2,20))\n    thumbs.append(canvas)\nfrom math import ceil\ncols=2\nrows=ceil(len(thumbs)/cols)\nW=cols*760+(cols+1)*20\nH=rows*1460+(rows+1)*20\nsheet=Image.new('RGB',(W,H),(245,245,245))\nfor idx,im in enumerate(thumbs):\n    r=idx//cols; c=idx%cols\n    x=20+c*(760+20); y=20+r*(1460+20)\n    sheet.paste(im,(x,y))\npath=os.path.join(outdir,'collage.jpg')\nsheet.save(path,quality=90)\nprint(path)\nPY","workdir":"/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/workspace","yieldMs":10000},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"python3 - <<'PY'\\nfrom PIL import Image\\npaths = [\\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/2f10c392-d5aa-47d8-8dff-7b402ac58524.jpg',\\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/f4c7fa5e-fd85-4c82-b36f-15e4a8e740a6.jpg',\\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/0a948e57-9eff-42ff-94d0-a97a4d2a0573.jpg',\\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/67c0c117-3a53-4ff2-bc5d-871ee2a1659b.jpg',\\n'/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/home/.openclaw/media/inbound/24471c79-44f9-4655-bd8c-985b31357a3e.jpg',\\n]\\noutdir='/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/workspace/tmp/upgrade_self_collage'\\nimport os\\nos.makedirs(outdir, exist_ok=True)\\nthumbs=[]\\nfor i,p in enumerate(paths,1):\\n    img=Image.open(p).convert('RGB')\\n    w,h=img.size\\n    crop=img.crop((0, int(h*0.12), w, int(h*0.88)))\\n    crop.thumbnail((700,1400))\\n    canvas=Image.new('RGB',(760,1460),'white')\\n    canvas.paste(crop,((760-crop.size[0])//2,20))\\n    thumbs.append(canvas)\\nfrom math import ceil\\ncols=2\\nrows=ceil(len(thumbs)/cols)\\nW=cols*760+(cols+1)*20\\nH=rows*1460+(rows+1)*20\\nsheet=Image.new('RGB',(W,H),(245,245,245))\\nfor idx,im in enumerate(thumbs):\\n    r=idx//cols; c=idx%cols\\n    x=20+c*(760+20); y=20+r*(1460+20)\\n    sheet.paste(im,(x,y))\\npath=os.path.join(outdir,'collage.jpg')\\nsheet.save(path,quality=90)\\nprint(path)\\nPY\",\"workdir\":\"/vol1/@apphome/trim.openclaw/data/workspace\",\"yieldMs\":10000}"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openai","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":22941,"output":607,"cacheRead":15872,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39420,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777262626303,"responseId":"resp_06da932db866b0fd0169eee02522548193bc7353a08499f24e"}}
